229
00:19:59,220 --> 00:20:02,540
and moral history, social status, influence,

230
00:20:02,740 --> 00:20:05,680
intelligence, religious background, or the lack of it.

231
00:20:06,680 --> 00:20:09,760
To love like Jesus is to love inclusively,

232
00:20:09,760 --> 00:20:17,560
indiscriminately and universally when that kind of love flows within a congregation the world

233
00:20:17,560 --> 00:20:28,440
will take note that they have been with jesus that's when the community takes note do people

234
00:20:28,440 --> 00:20:35,720
see jesus in our actions toward each other here at fullerton first do we really love each other

235
00:20:35,720 --> 00:20:42,910
within this church or are we just friendly do we really love each other what about those with

236
00:20:42,910 --> 00:20:48,690
different political views? Can we still love each other really, honestly, from the core of our being?

237
00:20:50,790 --> 00:20:55,010
What about those with different views on different doctrines? Can we still love them authentically?

238
00:20:57,340 --> 00:21:03,830
Do we love those who are different from ourselves? The richness of a multi-generational church is a

239
00:21:03,830 --> 00:21:09,430
variety of people in different ages and stages. The challenge is we're in different ages and stages

240
00:21:09,430 --> 00:21:15,860
and sometimes hard to communicate. There's richness and there's problems at the same time.

241
00:21:15,860 --> 00:21:30,840
Can we overcome those things in the name of Jesus and really love each other and hear each other's stories and identify with each other, respect each other, love each other?

242
00:21:33,550 --> 00:21:34,390
I hope so.

243
00:21:34,730 --> 00:21:35,450
I think so.

244
00:21:35,670 --> 00:21:37,390
I think that is our experience here.

245
00:21:37,470 --> 00:21:38,750
I think it can grow even more.

246
00:21:41,160 --> 00:21:43,480
1 John 4.10 says this is real love.

247
00:21:44,260 --> 00:21:49,660
It's not that we have loved God, but that he loved us and sent his son as a sacrifice to take away our sins.

248
00:21:49,660 --> 00:21:55,300
Dear friends, since God loved us that much, we surely ought to love each other.

249
00:21:56,460 --> 00:21:58,200
We surely ought to love each other.

250
00:22:01,210 --> 00:22:03,010
What does that kind of love in action look like?

251
00:22:03,050 --> 00:22:03,830
Here's some ideas.

252
00:22:04,270 --> 00:22:05,370
Just a few ideas.

253
00:22:06,030 --> 00:22:08,570
It goes a lot further than this, but here's a few ideas.

254
00:22:09,950 --> 00:22:11,210
You want to love somebody in this church?

255
00:22:11,330 --> 00:22:12,390
Here's a challenge today.

256
00:22:13,480 --> 00:22:14,940
I've said it before, I'll say it again.

257
00:22:15,460 --> 00:22:20,800
Take out somebody to lunch today that you don't yet know from this church.

258
00:22:21,160 --> 00:22:23,300
And establish relationship.

259
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:25,820
That's bold, huh?

260
00:22:29,130 --> 00:22:31,230
I'd say I'd pay for it, but I can't afford it.

261
00:22:32,490 --> 00:22:33,670
You're going to have to do this on your own.

262
00:22:36,500 --> 00:22:38,100
Why don't you grab somebody you don't know?

263
00:22:38,700 --> 00:22:39,200
And you know what?

264
00:22:39,220 --> 00:22:40,060
Here's even bolder.

265
00:22:40,540 --> 00:22:45,110
Young people, grab a grandfather or grandmother you don't know yet.

266
00:22:47,310 --> 00:22:50,790
Grandmas and grandpas, fathers and mothers, grab somebody young that you don't know yet

267
00:22:50,790 --> 00:22:52,970
and share your life across generations.

268
00:22:53,950 --> 00:22:54,470
That's love.

269
00:22:56,470 --> 00:23:02,840
The waitress will think you're their child and vice versa and say, no, we're a church.

270
00:23:02,920 --> 00:23:03,860
We want to get to know each other.

271
00:23:03,860 --> 00:23:04,780
That'll blow them away.

272
00:23:06,130 --> 00:23:06,630
That's love.

273
00:23:08,230 --> 00:23:11,050
Weep with those who weep in the congregation.

274
00:23:12,700 --> 00:23:13,300
That's love.

275
00:23:14,930 --> 00:23:18,920
Bless somebody from the church by taking them out to do what they love to do.

276
00:23:20,080 --> 00:23:21,100
Spend time in their world.

277
00:23:24,510 --> 00:23:25,730
How do you love in the family?

278
00:23:25,790 --> 00:23:26,970
Here's some practical ones.

279
00:23:28,160 --> 00:23:29,300
I struggle with some of these too.

280
00:23:30,230 --> 00:23:35,570
Do your part in the house to keep it clean so that you won't have to be nagged by the other spouse.

281
00:23:38,770 --> 00:23:39,310
Oh, boy.

282
00:23:39,310 --> 00:23:47,830
Why don't you ask your children, your grandchildren, about their homework.

283
00:23:49,320 --> 00:23:50,160
Come alongside.

284
00:23:53,240 --> 00:23:54,100
Get into it with them.

285
00:23:57,620 --> 00:23:59,060
Young fathers, this is for you.

286
00:23:59,740 --> 00:24:00,340
Just a thought.

287
00:24:01,180 --> 00:24:06,420
When the baby cries in the middle of the night, you get up so Mom can get some rest.

288
00:24:07,280 --> 00:24:07,980
There's an idea.

289
00:24:10,220 --> 00:24:12,280
Don't just roll over and pretend you didn't hear.

290
00:24:12,820 --> 00:24:14,300
I pulled that stunt a couple times.

291
00:24:16,290 --> 00:24:16,710
Mm-hmm.

292
00:24:18,370 --> 00:24:19,270
Come on.

293
00:24:19,710 --> 00:24:20,950
Dads, we can do better than that.

294
00:24:22,820 --> 00:24:23,440
That's love.

295
00:24:25,520 --> 00:24:28,320
Make an offer to wash the dishes, mow the grass, cook the dinner,

296
00:24:28,520 --> 00:24:29,480
watch the neighbor's kids.

297
00:24:29,580 --> 00:24:30,220
It goes on and on.

298
00:24:30,240 --> 00:24:30,820
You get the idea.

299
00:24:33,160 --> 00:24:35,860
Take your teenage daughter or granddaughter out on a date.

300
00:24:36,400 --> 00:24:36,880
Just talk.

301
00:24:37,040 --> 00:24:37,560
Just listen.

302
00:24:39,070 --> 00:24:39,930
Get into their world.

303
00:24:41,280 --> 00:24:44,180
That's how you wash the feet of each other in practical ways.

304
00:24:44,420 --> 00:24:46,660
And that's just a little teaser of a list.

305
00:24:46,920 --> 00:24:49,000
You can extrapolate that as God leads.

306
00:24:49,080 --> 00:24:49,880
You get the idea.

307
00:24:51,070 --> 00:24:52,250
But practical things.

308
00:24:53,780 --> 00:24:56,260
When you do those kinds of things, you're taking the initiative.

309
00:24:56,400 --> 00:24:58,700
You are, in a sense, washing somebody's feet.

310
00:24:58,700 --> 00:25:05,480
You're doing the little things that bless somebody else, not because you have to, but

311
00:25:05,480 --> 00:25:08,580
because you really love them and you want to serve them.

312
00:25:09,240 --> 00:25:09,800
Because why?

313
00:25:09,900 --> 00:25:13,920
Because your future is secure, your past is clean, you're free in the present to love.

314
00:25:18,210 --> 00:25:18,870
It's a true story.

315
00:25:21,420 --> 00:25:26,320
Marian Mill was born in a fairytale royal palace in the country of Hungary.

316
00:25:27,860 --> 00:25:34,120
Her first spoon was literally solid gold, not a figure of speech, it actually was.

317
00:25:35,470 --> 00:25:38,310
They sent her to school in Vienna where she became an actress.

318
00:25:38,610 --> 00:25:42,590
And then she met and fell in love with a young medical student named Otto.

319
00:25:43,870 --> 00:25:48,230
Otto and Marion married and went to live in Hollywood, California.

320
00:25:49,750 --> 00:25:53,450
And there as they set up house, they began to dabble in the movies.

321
00:25:54,880 --> 00:25:59,240
And Otto became interested in movies so much that he gave up his medical practice

322
00:25:59,240 --> 00:26:03,900
and went on to become the internationally famed director Otto Preminger.

323
00:26:06,380 --> 00:26:11,440
Marion's beauty, her wit, her irresistible charm brought her everything a woman can desire.

324
00:26:12,880 --> 00:26:17,780
In Europe, New York, Hollywood, she became a famous hostess on that social scene.

325
00:26:19,200 --> 00:26:22,460
But Otto's princess could not handle the fast life of Hollywood.

326
00:26:24,160 --> 00:26:27,220
She went to alcohol, drugs, and numerous affairs.

327
00:26:27,840 --> 00:26:34,800
Her life and her lifestyle became so sordid, even for Hollywood, that Otto Preminger finally divorced her.

328
00:26:35,830 --> 00:26:37,810
She tried to take her own life three times.

329
00:26:37,930 --> 00:26:41,450
unsuccessfully, and finally moved back to Vienna.

330
00:26:43,220 --> 00:26:47,470
And there it was, at a party, that she met another doctor

331
00:26:47,470 --> 00:26:52,700
named Albert Schweitzer. The well-known doctor,

332
00:26:52,860 --> 00:26:55,820
musician, philosopher, theologian, and missionary.

333
00:26:57,620 --> 00:27:01,480
And Schweitzer happened to be on home leave at the time, and he had been working

334
00:27:01,480 --> 00:27:04,500
in a hospital in Lamberine, I think I'm pronouncing that right, Africa.

335
00:27:05,000 --> 00:27:09,440
And she was so fascinated by Schweitzer at this party, that she asked him if she could

336
00:27:09,440 --> 00:27:15,670
talked him alone. And he permitted that. He allowed her to meet. And for almost six months,

337
00:27:15,730 --> 00:27:22,140
every week, she met with Dr. Albert Schweitzer. At the end of that time, he was going back

338
00:27:22,140 --> 00:27:29,280
to Africa. She begged him to let her go with him. And Schweitzer surprised everyone, and

339
00:27:29,280 --> 00:27:36,680
he said yes. And he agreed to take her back to Africa. And they went back, this young

340
00:27:36,680 --> 00:27:44,080
princess and the doctor. Born in a palace, now she's serving in this little hospital

341
00:27:44,080 --> 00:27:50,640
in Africa. And she spent the rest of her life emptying bedpans and tearing up sheets to make

342
00:27:50,640 --> 00:27:59,190
bandages for the putrid sores on the bodies of these stricken people in a poverty-stricken,

343
00:27:59,330 --> 00:28:04,040
impoverished land. And when she wrote her autobiography, and it was called this,

344
00:28:04,320 --> 00:28:11,600
All I Want is Everything. It's a great title. In that autobiography, she wrote some profound words.

345
00:28:11,600 --> 00:28:16,680
When she died, Time Magazine quoted these words from that autobiography.

346
00:28:17,940 --> 00:28:20,500
Quote, Albert Schweitzer says,

347
00:28:20,660 --> 00:28:21,920
There are two kinds of people.

348
00:28:23,020 --> 00:28:26,440
There are the helpers and the non-helpers.

349
00:28:27,910 --> 00:28:31,470
I thank God he allowed me to become a helper.

350
00:28:32,350 --> 00:28:36,130
And in helping, I found everything.

351
00:28:38,780 --> 00:28:39,440
Isn't that amazing?

352
00:28:40,930 --> 00:28:45,040
The princess serving in the impoverished land.

353
00:28:45,040 --> 00:28:48,540
And in serving, she found everything.

354
00:28:50,110 --> 00:28:53,070
In giving herself away, she found the path to blessing.

355
00:28:54,180 --> 00:28:55,240
Just like Jesus said.

356
00:28:57,970 --> 00:28:59,850
She discovered a truth that's stranger than fiction.

357
00:28:59,970 --> 00:29:04,630
When you spend your life seeking to satisfy, the result is misery.

358
00:29:05,800 --> 00:29:11,960
On the other hand, if you consistently give yourself away, you gain more than you can ever imagine.

359
00:29:14,480 --> 00:29:16,620
So the point is, there's a payoff in serving.

360
00:29:17,920 --> 00:29:19,460
You gain when you give yourself away.

361
00:29:20,400 --> 00:29:21,000
We really do.

362
00:29:25,390 --> 00:29:28,950
The one who truly did that in a way that probably is the most profound

363
00:29:28,950 --> 00:29:30,830
and strikes me the most is Jim Elliott.

364
00:29:32,460 --> 00:29:36,080
An extreme example, but one that motivates and challenges me,

365
00:29:36,240 --> 00:29:41,770
Jim was a missionary to reach the Alka Indians, South America,

366
00:29:42,710 --> 00:29:44,490
and he gave his life for that cause.

367
00:29:47,790 --> 00:29:49,190
And yet then his wife went back,

368
00:29:49,550 --> 00:29:54,170
and she was able to bring Jesus to those people,

369
00:29:54,630 --> 00:29:57,420
and the whole village came to Christ.

370
00:29:59,360 --> 00:30:03,890
And he penned some words that have been real motivating to me.

371
00:30:06,270 --> 00:30:14,810
He is no fool who gives up what he cannot keep to gain that which he will never lose.

372
00:30:16,430 --> 00:30:18,590
That's Jesus' words, paraphrased, aren't they?

373
00:30:18,910 --> 00:30:26,020
He is no fool who gives up what he cannot keep to gain that which he will never lose.

374
00:30:27,320 --> 00:30:30,340
Let's hear that again in the form of a song.

